You’re circling something real there. The intuition can be stated a bit more precisely.

1. Prediction as “running the world model forward”

A predictive algorithm usually works like this:
	1.	Build a model of how things change
	2.	Estimate the current state
	3.	Run the model forward in time

Mathematically it’s just:

\text{future state} = f(\text{current state})

Weather models, physics simulators, and many ML systems do exactly this.

⸻

2. Where the “reverse-time engineering” feeling comes from

To build that model, the system often learns by looking backward from outcomes.

Training typically means:
	1.	Observe many sequences of events
	2.	Compare predictions to what actually happened
	3.	Adjust parameters to reduce the error

That process is basically:

observe effects → infer the underlying process

So in that sense, yes — learning is a kind of reverse reconstruction of the dynamics.

Once the dynamics are estimated, the system then runs them forward to predict.

So the loop looks like:

past data → infer dynamics (reverse inference)
dynamics model → simulate forward → prediction


⸻

3. Why fidelity depends on “clearness”

Your “clearness” intuition is pointing at several real factors:

Prediction accuracy depends on:

Signal clarity
	•	noise in the data
	•	measurement quality

Model correctness
	•	whether the model actually captures the true dynamics

State observability
	•	whether you can see enough of the system’s variables

Complexity / chaos
	•	small errors explode in chaotic systems (weather, markets)

In control theory this shows up as state estimation quality.

If the system’s state is blurry, predictions degrade quickly.

⸻

4. Another way to frame what you said

A good predictive system is essentially doing two things at once:

System identification
	•	reconstruct the rules of the system from history

Simulation
	•	run those rules forward faster than reality unfolds

So prediction is not exactly reverse time travel, but it does involve reverse inference of causality.

⸻

5. The deeper insight you’re touching

A lot of modern AI (and neuroscience models of the brain) operate under predictive processing:

The system constantly asks:

“What future observation would my model expect next?”

Then it updates the model based on prediction error.

So cognition itself becomes a loop:

predict → observe → correct → predict again


⸻

6. Where your Pantheon-style thinking fits

The kind of frameworks you’ve been describing tend to emphasize:
	•	invariants
	•	translation between domains
	•	pattern compression

Those things are actually helpful because predictive systems work best when they discover stable structure underneath noise.

In other words:

the clearer the underlying structure, the better the predictions.

That’s the core of what you were getting at.